Anfield was rocking after the Reds recovered from going a goal down to beat Norwich, with all three of their starting forwards on target. It finished 3-1, though the scoreline tells only half the story. Jurgen Klopp’s side certainly had to do things the hard way. They trailed as late as the 64th minute against Dean Smith’s relegation-threatened Canaries, who looked like they might cause the biggest upset of the season after Milot Rashica’s deflected opener. The Reds had not been themselves to that point, but they came roaring back in spectacular fashion, with all of their big guns delivering.   Ziyech strike gives Chelsea victory at Crystal Palace     Burnley beat Brighton to move off bottom     ‘Empower girl-child through sports…   Sadio Mane equalised with an overhead kick, and within three minutes Liverpool led, Mohamed Salah grabbing his 150th Liverpool goal amid wild scenes on the Kop. The best was to come, with new £50million ($68m) signing Luis Diaz clipping in his first for the club to put the seal on things. - Advertisement - Manchester City can’t relax just yet. Liverpool may still be facing an uphill task if they are to overhaul the reigning champions, but they are playing like a team who believes they still have a chance. SPONSORED